04054nam a22006375i 9780748674374DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20221999stk    fo  d z      eng d  a97807486743747 a10.1515/97807486743742doi  a(DE-B1597)615296  a(OCoLC)1322124991  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  astkcGB-SCT 7aLIT0041202bisacsh1 aCraig, Cairns, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Modern Scottish Novel :bNarrative and the National Imagination /cCairns Craig. 1aEdinburgh : bEdinburgh University Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©1999  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction: Novel, Nation, Tradition -- t1. Fearful Selves: Character, Community and the Scottish Imagination -- t2. Dialect and Dialectics -- t3. Enduring Histories: Mythic Regions -- t4. The Typographic Muse -- t5. Doubtful Imaginings -- tConclusion: Narrative and the Space of the Nation -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the last quarter century, Scottish novelists from Muriel Spark, Alasdair Gray and Allan Massie to James Kelman, Janice Galloway, A.L. Kennedy and Irvine Welsh have achieved significant international success. In The Modern Scottish Novel Cairns Craig shows how the work of such writers is constructed by a powerful national tradition in the novel, formed in the first decades of the century by writers such as John Buchan, Nan Shepherd, Lewis Grassic Gibbon and Neil Gunn, a tradition whose distinctive thematic and formal concerns have shaped a unique contribution to the novel in English. Tracing the influence of Scotland's political and social history on its novelists from the 1890s to the 1990s, Craig argues that the Scottish novel has had to develop a highly specific set of formal techniques to cope with a situation in which the dominance of the English language is challenged by the survival of the rich inheritance of Scots speech, and in which the continuing effects of Calvinism imply that all fiction is necessarily deceitful, when not actually diabolic. Craig also sets the Scottish novel in the specific traditions of Scottish intellectual life - from J.G. Frazer to John Macmurray and R.D. Laing. The Modern Scottish Novel provides the intellectual and artistic context for some of the most exciting and challenging contemporary writing in English.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z97831107804750 cprintz978074860893540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978074867437440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780748674374423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780748674374/original  a978-3-11-078047-5  Edinburgh University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK